provenance.note:
Owned and annotated by Blake c. 1798; probably acquired by Blake's wife, Catherine, upon his death in 1827; acquired by “Samuel Palmer/1833” (according to the note on the first endpaper); 
                    presumably passed on to his son, A. H. Palmer, upon his father’s death in 1881; 
                    held by Lionel Isaacs of the Haymarket in London c. 1900 (according to Geoffrey Keynes, *A Bibliography of William Blake* [New York: Grolier Club, 1921], page 51); 
                    acquired by bookseller George T. Goodspeed no earlier than c. 1900 and no later than c. 1929 (according to Geoffrey Keynes, *The Gates of Memory* [Oxford: Clarendon P, 1981], page 301); 
                    acquired by Josiah K. Lilly, Jr. from Goodspeed's of Boston c. 1929; sold by Lilly to Geoffrey Keynes for $1,000 in 1947 (according to Keynes, *The Gates of Memory*, page 302); 
                    acquired by Cambridge University Library by bequest upon Keynes’ death in 1982.
